{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "It is easily verified, that this subspace is weak * closed in L ∞ ([0, 1] d, k R d).",
    "Suppose first that η is of the formη = η 1 dx 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dx k+1 (7.2)and observe that since k + 1 ≤ d, if η 1 is not identically zero, then neither is η.Let ω be a Lipschitz map solving (7.1) a.e.",
    "For every I = (i 1,..., i k) where i 1 < • • • < i k, i 1,..., i k ∈ {1,..., d}, we find a Lipschitz real-valued map ω I such thatω = I ω I dx I = I ω I dx i 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dx i k.For any j = {1,..., k + 1}, let I j = (1,..., j -1, j + 1,..., k + 1).Then, by considering the projection of dω to the basis vector dx 1 ∧ • • • ∧ dx k+1, the equality (7.1) in particular implies k+1 j=1 (-1) j-1 ∂ω I j ∂e j = η 1.",
    "(7.3)Finally, since the equality holds almost everywhere, by Fubini's theorem, it also holds L k+1a.e.",
    "on at least one (in fact almost every) section of the cube [0, 1] d by the plane spanned by e 1,..., e k+1."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "It is easily verified, that this subspace is weak * closed in L ∞ ([0, 1] d, k R d).",
    "on at least one (in fact almost every) section of the cube [0, 1] d by the plane spanned by e 1,..., e k+1."
